@startuml fig-ftp-active-vs-passive
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title FTP: Active Mode vs Passive Mode

participant "Client\n(behind NAT)" as C #FFE0B2
participant "NAT /\nFirewall" as FW #FFCDD2
participant "FTP Server" as S #C8E6C9

== ACTIVE MODE (server initiates data connection) ==

C -> S : TCP 21: PORT client_ip,client_port
S --> C : 200 PORT command successful

S -[#E53935]>x FW : TCP from server:20 → client:client_port
note right of FW #FFEBEE
  Blocked: NAT/firewall drops
  inbound connections to client
end note

== PASSIVE MODE (client initiates data connection) ==

C -> S : TCP 21: PASV
S --> C : 227 (server_ip,p1,p2)

C -[#43A047]> S : TCP from client:ephemeral → server:passive_port
note right of S #E8F5E9
  Success: client initiates both
  control and data connections
end note

S -[#43A047]-> C : <data transfer>
S --> C : 226 Transfer complete

legend right
  Active mode fails when clients sit behind
  NAT because the server cannot reach back.
  Passive mode solves this by letting the
  client open both connections outward.
  Modern networks almost always use PASV.
endlegend
@enduml
